# 四、Band 8 改写版（建议精读）

The line graph compares female employment rates among women aged 15 to 64 in five countries between 2003 and 2009.

Overall, the UK maintained the highest female employment rates throughout the period, whereas Turkey consistently recorded the lowest figures. In most countries, employment rates increased over time, although Turkey experienced an overall decline despite a slight recovery at the end of the period.

In 2003, approximately 80% of women in the UK were employed, compared with around 70% in Canada. The figure for the UK rose marginally to about 84% in 2007 before falling slightly back to 80% in 2009. Canada, by contrast, saw its employment rate decline from 70% to 65% in 2005, after which it recovered steadily to reach approximately 75% by the end of the period.

Germany and Chile both experienced gradual growth in female employment. Germany’s employment rate increased steadily from about 50% in 2003 to 65% in 2009, while the figure for Chile rose from 40% to 50% over the same period. Turkey showed a contrasting pattern, as its employment rate fell significantly from approximately 20% in 2003 to just 10% in 2007, before recovering modestly to around 15% in 2009.

